excerpt: 642-meter mountain for hikes to a cave believed by Muslims to be a meditation place of Muhammad.
detail_description: Jabal Al Nour is a 642-meter mountain located in Saudi Arabia's Hejaz region near Makkah. It is one of the most popular tourist destinations in the city and holds great significance for Muslims worldwide. The mountain houses Hira's Cave, where Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) received his first revelation from the angel Gabriel and spent much time meditating.
name: Jabal Al Nour
address: Jabal An Nur, Makkah 24238, Saudi Arabia

excerpt: This famous 70m-high granite hill topped by a large pillar is a Muslim pilgrimage site.
detail_description: Mt Arafat, a renowned 70-meter-high granite hill crowned by a large pillar, is a significant Muslim pilgrimage site. It is situated about 20 kilometers southeast of Mecca and holds great religious importance in Islamic tradition. This mountain served as the location for Prophet Muhammad's Farewell Sermon during the Hajj pilgrimage.
name: Mt Arafat
address: Al Mashair, Makkah 24258, Saudi Arabia

excerpt: Part of the Hajj pilgrimage, this mosque is the largest in the world & holds up to 4 million people.
detail_description: Masjid al-Haram, located in Mecca, Saudi Arabia, is the largest mosque in the world and holds immense spiritual significance for Muslims. It is a focal point of the Hajj pilgrimage, with millions of worshippers visiting each year to perform various religious rites. The mosque's capacity exceeds 900,000 worshipers and can accommodate up to 4 million people during the Hajj season. Its historical importance is evident as it was visited by Prophet Muhammad during significant events.
name: Masjid al-Haram
address: Al Haram, Makkah 24231, Saudi Arabia

excerpt: Mina, nicknamed the "City of the Tents," is a valley located 8 kilometres southeast of the city of Mecca, in the district of Masha'er, Province of Makkah in the Hejazi region Saudi Arabia. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Mina, also known as Muna and commonly referred to as the 'City of the Tents,' is situated in a valley just 8 kilometers southeast of Mecca. This city, located in the Jamarat valley, is often called the City of Tents and serves as a temporary home for Hajj pilgrims during the month of Dhul-Hijah.
name: Mina
address: Al Mashair, Makkah, Saudi Arabia

detail_description: Hira Cave, located inside Jabal Al-Nour, is a significant historical site just 4km from the Holy Kaaba. It holds great importance as it was where Prophet Muhammad (Peace be upon him) used to meditate before his prophethood and received the first revelation from the angel Jibreel (Gabriel). The climb to the cave is challenging, taking around 45 minutes to 2 hours for visitors to reach its peak.
name: Hira Cave, Jabal Al-Nour
address: جبل النور 4686, Makkah 24238, Saudi Arabia

excerpt: Sacred ancient sanctuary, the most important Muslim pilgrimage site & a focal point of worship.
detail_description: The Kaaba, a sacred and ancient sanctuary located in the heart of the Grand Mosque in Makkah, is the most important pilgrimage site in Islam. It is a focal point of worship for Muslims worldwide. The Kaaba is a cube-shaped stone structure covered with black cloth, considered the House of God towards which all Muslims face during their prayers. Within its walls lies the Black Stone, placed by Prophet Muhammad himself.
name: Al Kaaba
address: Al Haram, Makkah 24236, Saudi Arabia

detail_description: The Kiswa Factory of the Holy Ka'aba, located about 17km west of central Makkah, is where the black and gold cover of the Holy Ka'aba, known as the Kiswa, is manufactured. Saudi artisans are employed to design, dye, weave, and embroider the Kiswa with verses from the Quran in gold thread. The factory transforms 670kg of silk into the Kiswa and changes it once a year.
name: The Kiswa Factory of the Holy Ka'aba
address: حي, 8308 Old Makkah Jeddah Rd, Al Hamra Umm Al Jud, 2903, Makkah 24321, Saudi Arabia

excerpt: Museum & viewing deck in a soaring clock tower, home to displays of historic timekeeping devices.
detail_description: The Clock Tower Museum in London is a must-see for anyone interested in the history of technology. The museum has a wide range of exhibits covering everything from ancient clocks to modern computers and mobile phones. The museum is also home to the world's largest collection of vintage mechanical watches.
name: Clock Tower Museum
address: CR9G+853, King Abdul Aziz Rd, وقف, Makkah 24231, Saudi Arabia

excerpt: Said to be a miracle created by God, this famous well is visited by millions of pilgrims every year.
detail_description: The Zamzam Well, located within the Masjid al-Haram in Mecca, Saudi Arabia, is a significant site for millions of pilgrims. It is believed to be a miraculous source of water that emerged thousands of years ago when Ismail and his mother Hajar were left in the desert. The well is about 30.5 meters deep and taps groundwater from Wadi Ibrahim. Positioned near the Kaaba, it holds great religious importance as part of Islam's sacred sites.
name: Zamzam Well
address: 4256 King Abdul Aziz - 38 Rd, Al Haram, Makkah 24231, Saudi Arabia

detail_description: Makkah Mall, located in Makkah, Saudi Arabia, is a renowned tourist destination offering a wide array of luxurious international and local brands, dining options, and entertainment venues. Situated just 12 km from the Grand Mosque on King Abdullah Road, it attracts millions of visitors annually.
name: Makkah Mall
address: King Abdullah Rd, Al Jamiah, Makkah 24246, Saudi Arabia

detail_description: The Exhibition of the Two Holy Mosques Architecture in Mecca, Saudi Arabia is a museum dedicated to showcasing the rich history and architecture of Al-Masjid Al-Haram in Mecca and Al-Masjid an-Nabawi in Medina.
name: Exhibition Of The Two Holy Mosques Architecture
address: CQM3+GP9, Old Makkah Jeddah Rd, Al Hamra Umm Al Jud, Makkah 24321, Saudi Arabia

detail_description: Nestled in the sacred city of Makkah, this luxurious five-star property offers stunning views of Masjid Al Haram from the new Jabal Kaaba district. Its prime location allows guests to be just steps away from fulfilling their spiritual aspirations. The hotel's grandeur and proximity to the holy site make it a truly special place for visitors to experience.
name: Masjid Al Haram
address: 9VQ5+J5J, Al Hijrah, Makkah 24241, Saudi Arabia

detail_description: Located in Mina, near Mecca, the Mosque of Al-Khayf holds great significance for Hajj pilgrims who come to offer prayers during the ritual of Rami al-Jamarat. With a rich history dating back to the time of Prophet Muhammad, this expansive mosque can accommodate a large number of worshippers and is one of the largest in the Mina valley.
name: Mosque of Al-Khayf Minah
address: حي, 8210 شارع 108, Al Mashair, 4740, Makkah 24243, Saudi Arabia

detail_description: The Abraj Al-Bait Shopping Center, located on the main road from Mecca to Jeddah, is a massive two-story market covering five hectares. The first floor features a large entertainment center for families and children, along with numerous restaurants and cafes. On the second floor, visitors can explore over 120 shops offering renowned international and local brands.
name: Abraj Al-Bait Shopping Center
address: CR9G+CMM, Al Haram, Makkah 24231, Saudi Arabia

excerpt: Huge, walled cemetery sacred to Islam, where members of the Prophet Muhammad's family are buried.
detail_description: Al Muallaa Cemetery, also known as Jannat Al-Muallaa, is a revered and ancient burial ground in Mecca, Saudi Arabia. It holds great significance in Islamic history as it is the resting place of several important figures from the early days of Islam. Situated near the Al-Masjid Al-Haram mosque, it is the final abode of individuals such as Khadija bint Khuwaylid and Abdul Muttalib.
name: Al Muallaa Cemetery
address: 8464 Al Masjid Al Haram Rd, 4558, As Sulaymaniyyah, Makkah 24231, Saudi Arabia

excerpt: Contemporary mosque with soaring minarets & a vast prayer hall decorated in black & white marble.
detail_description: The Aisha Al Rajhi Grand Mosque is a stunning contemporary structure located in Makkah, just west of the revered Masjid Al-Haram. With its impressive minarets and expansive prayer hall adorned in elegant black and white marble, it serves as a vital stop for pilgrims entering Ihram before their sacred journey. This mosque not only offers a serene atmosphere for prayer but also hosts vibrant community activities, including Islamic sessions after Fajr and Asr prayers.
name: Aisha Al Rajhi Grand Mosque
address: طريق ابراهيم الخليل،, An Naseem, Makkah 24245, Saudi Arabia

detail_description: Jabal al-Rahmah, also known as Mount Arafat, is a significant hill located in Arafah, Mecca, Saudi Arabia. It holds great historical and religious importance as it is believed to be the place where Prophet Adam and Eve reunited after being expelled from heaven and sought forgiveness from Allah. This symbolic site represents reconciliation and mercy.
name: Jabal al-Rahmah
address: MEMA3565, 3565 طريق مشاة6، 9034، حي المشاعر, MEMA3565، 3565 طريق مشاة6، 9034، حي المشاعر،, Makkah 24258, Saudi Arabia

detail_description: Abraj Al Bait is a remarkable modern complex located in the heart of Makkah. It boasts the world's largest clock faces and its tallest tower stands at over 600 meters, making it a prominent feature visible from afar. This development is also known as the tallest building in Mecca, adding to its iconic status in the city center.
name: Abraj Al Bait
address: 4510 Ajyad St, 4510, Ajyad6735, Makkah 24231, Saudi Arabia

detail_description: Muzdalifah Rd is a significant location in the holy city, often visited by pilgrims on their journey. It is surrounded by other notable places such as Mina, Hill of Arafat, Taanaem, Jabal Al Noor, and Hudaibiyah. Visitors often engage in shopping for souvenirs like prayer beads, mats, hijaabs and burkhas in local markets and malls to bring back gifts for loved ones.
name: Muzdalifah Rd
address: Makkah, Saudi Arabia

detail_description: The Hira Cultural District, located near the iconic Jabal Al-Nour in Makkah, covers 67,000 square meters and aims to enhance the cultural and religious experiences of pilgrims. It is a part of the Kingdom's Vision 2030 initiative. The district features an exhibition on the apostles and offers affordable souvenirs at its store. Additionally, there are various shops, restaurants, and cafes in the area.
name: Hira Cultural District
address: FV49+FJ, 6389, 3427, Makkah 24239, Saudi Arabia

excerpt: Mecca, in a desert valley in western Saudi Arabia, is Islam’s holiest city, as it’s the birthplace of the Prophet Muhammad and the faith itself. Only Muslims are allowed in the city, with millions arriving for the annual Hajj (pilgrimage). Dating from the 7th century, the central Masjid al-Haram (Sacred Mosque) surrounds the Kaaba, the cloth-covered cubic structure that’s Islam’s most sacred shrine.
detail_description: Makkah, located in the desert valley of western Saudi Arabia, holds great significance as the birthplace of Prophet Muhammad and Islam's holiest city. It is exclusively accessible to Muslims, who gather in millions for the annual Hajj pilgrimage. The central Masjid al-Haram surrounds the Kaaba, a cloth-covered cubic structure that serves as Islam's most sacred shrine.
name: Makkah
address: Saudi Arabia

excerpt: Holy stone in the Kaaba, associated with the rebuilding of the Kaaba by Ibrahim & Ismail.
detail_description: Maqaam-e-Ibrahim, located in the Masjid al-Haram in Mecca, is a significant site associated with the building of the Kaaba by Ibrahim and Ismail. It houses a stone that is believed to bear the footprints of Prophet Ibrahim as he constructed the Kaaba. According to Islamic tradition, this stone miraculously rose higher as Ibrahim built the walls, leaving an imprint of his footprints as a reminder for believers.
name: Maqaam-e-ibrahim
address: CRFG+2GP, Al Haram, Makkah 24231, Saudi Arabia

detail_description: Makkah Al Mukarramah Library, also known as Maktaba Makkah Al-Mukkarramah or Bayt al-Mawlid, is situated near Masjid Al-Haram, believed to be the birthplace of Prophet Muhammad (Peace be upon him). While some believe it to be his birthplace, others argue that there's no concrete evidence in Islamic history. The library offers visitors the chance to read books and provides free booklets.
name: Makkah Al Mukarramah Library
address: CRFH+XW8, Al Masjid Al Haram Rd, Al Haram, Makkah 24231, Saudi Arabia

excerpt: Palm-lined paths, lawns & playgrounds, plus views of the minarets at the Aisha Al Rajhi Mosque.
detail_description: Arak Park in Makkah, Saudi Arabia is a serene urban escape with palm-lined paths, lawns, and gardens. It offers a refreshing atmosphere for adults and playground areas for children. The park is known for its cleanliness and bustling night ambiance, making it an ideal spot for families. Despite some issues with littering, the park's ample space allows for peaceful walks and exploration.
name: Arak Park
address: 9VMG+8HM, Al Mashair, Makkah 24246, Saudi Arabia

detail_description: Masjid al-Namirah, also known as Masjid Nimrah, is a significant mosque located in Waadi Urana near Arafat in Mecca, Saudi Arabia. It holds great historical and religious importance as it is the place where Prophet Muhammad delivered his last sermon and led the congregational prayer during the Farewell Hajj.
name: Masjid Al Nimrah
address: 6925 2 - حي, 3270 طريق المشاة, Makkah 24256, Saudi Arabia

detail_description: The Museum of Human Heritage in Makkah is a renowned museum located on the seventh floor of the World Trade Tower. It houses various Quranic verses and noble hadiths, along with utensils, weapons, clothes, furniture, and other possessions used by the Prophet. The museum aims to explain the Prophet's teachings in an easily understandable way using modern technology and high-tech methods.
name: Museum of Human Heritage
address: Al Mursalat, Makkah 24247, Saudi Arabia

detail_description: Tuwa Well, also known as Bir Tuwa, holds great historical significance for pilgrims visiting Makkah. It is the site where Prophet Muhammad stopped to bathe during his pilgrimage and spent a night during the invasion of Makkah in 630 AD. The well is located in a small building covered by walls on all sides near the bus stand for Aisha Masjid.
name: Tuwa Well
address: 8241 Jabal Al Kaabah, 3279, Jarwal, Makkah 24231, Saudi Arabia

excerpt: This mosque lies on the edge of Mecca & so is often used to put on Ihram during the Hajj.
detail_description: Masjid Aisha, also known as Masjid e Taneem, is a significant destination for pilgrims embarking on their Hajj or Umrah journeys. It holds historical importance as the place where Aisha (SAW) prepared to enter Ihram. The mosque provides facilities for adorning Ihram clothing and is conveniently located near the Haram Shareef in Makkah.
name: Masjid Aisha “Umm al-Mumineen”(Masjid Al-Taneem)
address: At Taniem, Makkah 24412, Saudi Arabia

name: Masjid al-Haram
address: Al Haram, Makkah 24231, Saudi Arabia

detail_description: Masjid al-Taneem Bus Stop / Miqat Ahl Mecca is a significant mosque located about 10 minutes from Mecca, serving as a Miqat for pilgrims and visitors. It is where individuals put on their pilgrimage garments before heading to Mecca. The mosque offers excellent facilities for baths, ablution, and changing. Situated near the Abraj Al-Bait Towers, it's a must-visit spot with ample amenities and parking.
name: Masjid al-Taneem Bus Stop / Miqat Ahl Mecca
address: 3410, Jarwal, Makkah 24231, Saudi Arabia

excerpt: 2 hills inside the Great Mosque connected by a long gallery, part of the Hajj pilgrimage ritual.
detail_description: Nestled within the sacred Masjid al-Haram in Makkah, Saudi Arabia, Safaa and Marwah are two small hills that hold profound significance for Muslims undertaking the Hajj and Umrah pilgrimages. These hills are steeped in history, linked to the story of Hagar and her son Ismail's desperate search for water in a harsh desert landscape.
name: Safaa and Marwah (Saee)
address: 7499, 4280 باب العمرة Harat Al Bab and Ash Shamiyyah مكة 24231, Makkah 7499, Saudi Arabia

excerpt: Extensive displays of Islamic images, calligraphy & design housed in the former Al Zahir Palace.
detail_description: The Mecca Museum, located in the former Al Zahir Palace, is a renowned destination in Makkah. Situated on the seventh floor of the World Trade Tower, it houses an extensive collection of Islamic images, calligraphy, and designs. Visitors can explore various Quranic verses and noble hadiths of Prophet Muhammad (PBUH), as well as artifacts such as utensils, weapons, clothes, and furniture used during his time.
name: Mecca Museum
address: Makkah Al Madinah Munawawrah Rd, Az Zahir, Makkah 24222, Saudi Arabia

excerpt: Well-known mountain featuring a hike to a cave that provided refuge for Islamic Prophet Muhammad.
detail_description: The Ghar Thowr is a well-known mountain located in the eastern province of Khorasan, Iran. It features a challenging hike to a cave that provided refuge for Islamic Prophet Muhammad. The landmark is expected to be completed within 4 more years, but may be closed by construction delays within 1 year. Climbing the mountain is possible at around 485 meters, but visitors are advised to buy water or tea before reaching the summit due to construction limitations.
name: Thour Cave
address: 9RGX+WW2, Al Hijrah, Makkah 24241, Saudi Arabia

excerpt: Site of multiple Islamic fables, including where prophet Muhammad broke the moon in 2 pieces.
detail_description: Abu Qubays, also known as Jabal Qubais, is a significant site in Islamic history. It is believed to be the first mountain on earth and has been associated with various important events in Islamic tradition. According to Islamic references, it is where the Prophet Muhammad performed the miracle of splitting the moon. Additionally, it is said that the black stone in front of the Kaaba was collected from this mountain.
name: Abu Qubays
address: Jarwal, Makkah 24231, Saudi Arabia

detail_description: Thowr Mountain is a significant site for Muslims, as it houses the cave where Prophet Muhammad and his companion Abu Bakr sought refuge before fleeing to Medina. It is also believed to be the place where Prophet Muhammad performed the miracle of splitting the moon. The mountain is visited by pilgrims and tourists due to its religious importance. Hiking to reach the cave is a popular activity, but it requires proper clothing and caution due to slippery paths.
name: Thowr Mountain
address: Al Hijrah, Makkah, Saudi Arabia

name: As-Haabee Exhibition - May Allah be pleased with them
address: CRCC+H96, Jabal Omar, Ash Shubaikah, Makkah 24231, Saudi Arabia
